The differences between Trump and Biden voters and their view on key issues

Introduction

The 2020 election was a tight race between Republican nominee President Donald Trump and Democratic nominee former Vice President Joe Biden. Trump won the 2016 presidential election with a majority of the Electoral College victory over Hillary Clinton but Clinton won the popular vote by nearly three percent. With the current COVID-19 pandemic, the election system has changed to accommodate the difficult circumstances with increasing mail-in ballots, early voting, vitual campaigns, etc. The election was held on November 3 and Joe Biden was elected as the 46th Pkresident of United States desipte Trumps effort to overturn the election with voter fraud claims that has no edvidence to support his allegations.

The dataset used in the following study is provided by the American National Election Studies(ANES) 2020 Exploratory Testing Survey conducted between April 10, 2020 and April 18, 2020. The dataset included responses from 3,080 adult citizens across the United States with questions regarding changes in the political environment and recent developments in social science research. The following analysis will focus on identifying the differences between Trump and Biden voters and their view in key issues issues to picture what might cause the lead to Trumps lost.

Exploration Data Analysis

Survey participants vote distribution

We first want to understand the distribution of the survey participants on who they voted for in the 2020 elections. The distribution shows that 43% of the participants voted for Biden while 40.8% voted for Trump. Looking back into the 2016 election, 37.5% of participants voted for Trump and 35.6% voted for Clinton while 21.3% did not vote.

For the participants who voted for Trump in 2016, 87.9% of them kept their choice and voted for Trump in 2020 while 7.8% changed their vote to Biden. For the participants who voted for Clinton in 2016, 87.5% of them voted for Biden in 2020 while 3.8% changed their vote to Trump. The number of people who did not vote in 2016 drop from 21.3% to 7.7% in 2020. Among those who decided to vote in 2020, 33.1% voted for Biden while 27% voted for Trump.

Voters demogphapics

Biden has more female voters while Trump has more male voters.

Biden has more voters with higher education than Bachelors degree while Trump has more voters with lower education.

Bidens voters have lower total household income than Trumps voters.

Most Bidens voters are Democrat and most Trumps voters are Republican but there is a higher percentage of Democrat voters voted for Trump than Republican voted for Biden. More independent voters voted for Biden than Trump.

Voters view on election accuracy and mail-in ballots

Overall, most voters believed that the 2020 election is accurate with higher percentage of Trump voters thinking the election results is completely accurate. However, the two group of voters have very different view on the accuracy of mail-in ballots. Bidens voter tend to support mail in ballots and strongly trusting the accuracy of voting by mail while Trumps vote tend to not support the mail in ballots and not at all believe in the accuracy of voting by mail. The strong disbelieve in mail in ballots has led Trumps vote to post election protest and supporting Trumps claim that the election was fraudulent.

Voter view on Trumps policies:

The two groups of voters have extreme views on the way Trump handles his job as president with Bidens voters mostly disapprove strongly while Trumps voters approved strongly. The vote responses on relations with foreign countries, immigration policies, economic policies, COVID response and health care policies all follow the same trend with extreme views from the two group of voters. However, there are more Bidens voters who approval Trumps economic policies over other issues.

Voter view on key issues:

COVID-19:

Overall, voters are somewhat worried about getting COVID but extremely worried about the upcoming economic impact. Most Trumps voters were not worried about catching COVID-19 but were moderately concern about the economic impact of the coronavirus while most Bidens voters were worried about getting COVID and extremely worried about the economic impact.

Abortion:

Trumps voters are against abortion and sugguest that abortion right should be tighten with laws while Bidens voters mostly believe that woman should always have abortion right and some support tightening abortion laws.

MeToo Movement:

Trumps voters believes that attention to sexual harassment from the #MeToo movement has gone too far while Bidens voters thinks its not gone far enough. Overall, most voters thinks its has been about right.
